of rights get out there,

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:09.650
why some products end up
being terrifically successful

00:02:09.650 --> 00:02:13.386
and others don't, why
some politicians--

00:02:13.386 --> 00:02:15.302
is it likely that someone
named Barack Hussein

00:02:15.302 --> 00:02:18.790
Obama would become president
of the United States?

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:20.530
I don't think that
was anticipated.

00:02:20.530 --> 00:02:22.190
It happened.

00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:24.000
Was it likely that
Donald Trump would

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.120
be the Republican nominee?

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:27.500
That wasn't anticipated.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:29.430
It looks like it's
going to happen.

00:02:29.430 --> 00:02:32.810
Why are rebellions
both so hard to predict

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:36.900
and often so massively
successful, like the Arab

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:38.420
Spring?

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:41.860
"Star Wars" success has
some similar features

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:44.650
I'm going to try to suggest.

00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:46.900
Here's the epigraph
for these remarks.

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:50.930
It's a dialogue between
two titans, George Lucas,

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:53.770
the mastermind of "Star
Wars," and Lawrence Kasdan,

00:02:53.770 --> 00:02:55.310
his co-author.

00:02:55.310 --> 00:03:00.110
Kasdan, a genius,
as Lucas is, sharply

00:03:00.110 --> 00:03:02.870
disagreed, the two of
them, on the question

00:03:02.870 --> 00:03:04.960
whether Luke or
somebody else should

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:07.340
die in "Return of the Jedi."

00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:10.090
And Kasdan said,
Luke should die.

00:03:10.090 --> 00:03:13.850
And Lucas said, Luke's
not going to die.

00:03:13.850 --> 00:03:16.460
And then Kasdan said, well,
someone else important

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:17.570
should die.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:20.580
And Lucas said, someone else
important is not going to die.

00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:22.480
You're a product of the '80s.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:24.610
This is not that kind of movie.

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:27.340
And Kasdan then said,
with evident feeling,

00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:30.310
I'm saying the movie has
more emotional weight

00:03:30.310 --> 00:03:33.000
if someone you love
is lost along the way.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:34.910
The journey has more impact.

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:36.970
That was a very
feeling-full statement

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:38.540
on the part of Kasdan.

00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:43.290
And Lucas responded,
apparently, very quickly, I

00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:46.880
don't like that, and
I don't believe that.

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:50.620
I think those are precious
words because of their immediacy

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:52.330
and clarity.

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:55.260
They're also behavioral
words in the sense

00:03:55.260 --> 00:04:00.240
that they track understanding
from behavioral science, which

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:02.550
is that often our
beliefs are motivated.

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:05.710
I don't like that, and
I don't believe that.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.391
That's Lucas' sequence.

00:04:08.391 --> 00:04:08.890
OK.

00:04:08.890 --> 00:04:11.440
So as of now, the
"Star Wars" movies

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:14.430
have made more than $30 billion.

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:18.769
That's more than the gross
domestic product of about 90

00:04:18.769 --> 00:04:20.990
of the world's nations.

00:04:20.990 --> 00:04:23.590
If "Star Wars" were
a nation, it would

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:28.780
rank about the middle of the
193 nations on the planet.

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:33.770
Doesn't it deserve its own
place at the United Nations?

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:37.340
It has become the
defining saga of our time.

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:40.990
President Obama ended a news
conference in December saying,

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:43.560
I've got to go see "Star Wars."

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:47.160
Secretary Clinton ended a
Democratic debate saying,

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:48.870
may the force be with you.

00:04:48.870 --> 00:04:54.720
And Senator Cruz tweeted before
one of the Republican debates

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:57.300
something that picked up
on "The Force Awakens."

00:04:57.300 --> 00:05:01.390
so it's bipartisan
and all-American.

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:06.840
Ironically and stunningly, no
one expected it to be a hit.

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:08.660
Nobody, really.

00:05:08.660 --> 00:05:12.760
Throughout its production at
Fox studios, there was apathy.

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:16.490
They hoped a lot of times
it would just go away.

00:05:16.490 --> 00:05:18.240
The movie theaters,
whose business

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:22.370
it is to predict success,
gave advance guarantees

00:05:22.370 --> 00:05:24.870
of $1.5 million.

00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:26.960
That's pathetic.

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:29.602
Fox's hope was $10 million.

00:05:29.602 --> 00:05:31.360
That's a low bar.

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:35.290
They couldn't get
close to the low bar.

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:39.260
Fox didn't even print
enough celluloid to meet

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:40.580
the early demand.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:44.270
They literally didn't think the
movie was worth the celluloid

00:05:44.270 --> 00:05:46.220
on which it was printed.

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:49.070
Right after "A New
Hope," originally

00:05:49.070 --> 00:05:52.490
called "Star Wars" opened,
George Lucas and spouse

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:55.220
went on vacation in Hawaii.

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:58.070
It was not just because
they needed a break.

00:05:58.070 --> 00:06:02.150
It's because they thought
they'd probably released a flop.

00:06:02.150 --> 00:06:05.440
In Hawaii, they could
escape what Lucas thought

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:07.450
might well be a disaster.

00:06:07.450 --> 00:06:09.970
The actors didn't have
much faith in it, either.

00:06:09.970 --> 00:06:13.260
Harrison Ford says there's
this giant guy walking around

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:14.470
in a dog suit.

00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:15.845
It was ridiculous.

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:19.110
OK.

00:06:19.110 --> 00:06:21.880
So we could think that
the success of "Star Wars"

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:24.330
had something to
do with the timing,

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:28.340
and this may have broad lessons
about products and politicians

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:33.010
and ideas that you have to hit
the culture in the right way

00:06:33.010 --> 00:06:34.180
at the right time.

00:06:34.180 --> 00:06:36.480
That's an external explanation.

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:40.140
Or you could have an internal
explanation, something

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:42.850
about the amazingness of the
thing whose success we're

00:06:42.850 --> 00:06:44.560
trying to explain.

00:06:44.560 --> 00:06:47.610
I'm going to go very
briskly over a series

00:06:47.610 --> 00:06:51.000
of possible explanations.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.930
And the external
explanations are

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:57.760
going to look very bad, to give
a little bit of the game away.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:00.800
There was a movie a few
years ago that won the Oscar.

00:07:00.800 --> 00:07:03.620
It's called "Searching
for Sugar Man,"

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:07.380
and it's about a rock singer
from the early 1970s named

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:12.300
Rodriguez, about whom even
connoisseurs of rock music

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:16.340
knew nothing because he released
two albums, as they were

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:18.490
then called, and they failed.

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:23.960
So think of this as one of a
zillion wanna-be rock stars who

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:26.440
flopped and ended
up, in this case,

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:30.910
going into the construction
business as a demolition man.

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:36.930
Unbeknownst to himself,
Rodriguez was, in South Africa,

00:07:36.930 --> 00:07:38.710
a giant.

00:07:38.710 --> 00:07:43.870
They would speak of him with
awe and reverence, Rodriguez.

00:07:43.870 --> 00:07:46.380
They wondered what
had happened to him.

00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:50.010
Had he burned himself
on stage, as rumors

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:53.640
had it, and thus
become an iconic kind

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:56.320
of self-immolating guy?

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:57.500
Now, there's a puzzle.

00:07:57.500 --> 00:08:01.050
Why did Rodriguez become
a runaway success--

00:08:01.050 --> 00:08:03.890
bigger than the Beatles,
really-- in South Africa

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:07.880
and kind of an utter failure
in the United States?

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:09.580
What's going on there?

00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:11.380
Well, I think we have
a little bit of clue

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:15.970
from "Harry Potter,"
where 12 publishers turned

00:08:15.970 --> 00:08:18.930
down the "Harry Potter" novels.

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:21.852
J.K. Rowling had a
struggle getting published.

00:08:21.852 --> 00:08:23.310
The publishers are
supposed to know

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:27.550
about quality and saleability.

00:08:27.550 --> 00:08:31.950
The advance originally for
"Harry Potter" was very small.

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:33.580
What happened there?

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:34.080
OK.

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:37.880
There's a strange tale
involving a mystery

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:39.361
writer named Robert Gottlieb.

00:08:39.361 --> 00:08:40.860
I'm not sure if
you've heard of him.

00:08:40.860 --> 00:08:43.480
He's written three
novels, the first of which

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:45.770
was called "The
Cuckoo's Calling."

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:48.410
"The Cuckoo's Calling"
was very well reviewed.

00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:50.330
Sold horribly.

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:52.330
So it was one of these
critical successes

00:08:52.330 --> 00:08:54.200
that was disappearing.

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:57.420
But it emerged, I
think, by happenstance

00:08:57.420 --> 00:09:00.010
that the real author of
"The Cuckoo's Calling"

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:03.540
is J.K. Rowling, and
the book exploded.

00:09:03.540 --> 00:09:05.290
Bestsellers.

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:07.050
What's going on there?

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:09.740
William Blake, one of
the most revered poets

00:09:09.740 --> 00:09:12.860
in the English language,
disappeared from the canon

00:09:12.860 --> 00:09:14.380
for a long time.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.692
Jane Austen herself
was-- and I'm

00:09:16.692 --> 00:09:18.400
trying to see if you're
paying attention,

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:20.990
because it's misspelled
there-- Jane Austen

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:26.370
was one of several
novelists in her era,

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:28.470
and she was not
thought to be the best.

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:31.480
Why did Jane Austen
and William Blake

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:35.330
turn out to be canonical
where people who at the time

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:38.921
were thought to be better
have, in fact, dropped out?

00:09:38.921 --> 00:09:39.420
OK.

00:09:39.420 --> 00:09:40.270
Here's a clue.

00:09:40.270 --> 00:09:44.590
This is an experiment a few
years ago, online experiment,

00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:46.530
where-- it's called
the music lab,

00:09:46.530 --> 00:09:48.240
where there's a
real website which

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:49.750
has dozens of songs on it.

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:52.560
In the control condition,
you can go on the website

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:55.380
and download the songs you like.

00:09:55.380 --> 00:09:56.540
That's the control.

00:09:56.540 --> 00:09:58.970
And that measure gives
an independent measure

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:00.740
of popularity.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:04.600
In eight subgroups,
something different happened,

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:08.410
which is you could see in
your randomly sorted group--

00:10:08.410 --> 00:10:11.260
the group into which you've
been randomly placed--

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:16.689
you can see how many people had
downloaded all of the songs.

00:10:16.689 --> 00:10:18.230
So there's a control
condition, where

00:10:18.230 --> 00:10:19.990
you don't see the
social influences,

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:22.190
you don't see what's
happened to other people,

00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:24.470
and there are eight
other groups, where

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:26.790
you can see how
the songs are doing

00:10:26.790 --> 00:10:31.120
with the relevant population
of 1,000 visitors, thousands

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:32.330
of visitors.

00:10:32.330 --> 00:10:32.830
OK.

00:10:32.830 --> 00:10:35.610
If intrinsic quality
is what mattered,

00:10:35.610 --> 00:10:38.210
you'd predict that
the eight worlds where

00:10:38.210 --> 00:10:40.870
you saw the initial
downloads would turn out

00:10:40.870 --> 00:10:43.080
to be the same as the
control condition.

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:45.830
Yes, quality [? would ?]
[? out. ?] And that's a very

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:48.360
plausible hypothesis.

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.820
That's not what happened.

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:56.000
Basically, while the best
songs never completely tanked

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.410
and the worst songs were
never spectacular successes,

00:11:00.410 --> 00:11:04.040
otherwise, anything
could happen.

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:07.920
A song which did very
poorly in one world

00:11:07.920 --> 00:11:12.920
could do very well in another,
where the only difference was

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:16.280
that it got initial downloads.

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:19.370
A song that did very
well in most worlds

00:11:19.370 --> 00:11:21.570
could tank in others,
and the reason

00:11:21.570 --> 00:11:24.940
is it didn't get a lot
of initial downloads.

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:28.370
Now, this is a profound
explanation, I think,

00:11:28.370 --> 00:11:32.350
of success and failure
in terms of movies,

00:11:32.350 --> 00:11:35.680
products of all kinds,
books, political candidates,

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:36.880
and ideas.

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:41.770
The question is, is there an
initial burst of enthusiasm

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:44.690
which zillions of
other people see?

00:11:44.690 --> 00:11:47.780
When that happens, something
whose intrinsic quality

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:50.640
isn't higher than
that of other things

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:56.570
can be culturally very resonant.

00:11:56.570 --> 00:11:59.820
Not because of the
culture, but because

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:03.090
of the relative happenstance
that a number of people

00:12:03.090 --> 00:12:06.060
got excited about it early.

00:12:06.060 --> 00:12:06.560
OK.

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:09.010
In terms of theory, what
we're speaking about here

00:12:09.010 --> 00:12:11.310
is cascades.

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:12.950
There are two kinds of cascades.

00:12:12.950 --> 00:12:16.150
One is informational and
the other is reputational.

00:12:16.150 --> 00:12:18.480
An informational
cascade is when you're

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:21.020
in a kind of temporal queue.

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:24.110
You're deciding among
five products, let's say.

00:12:24.110 --> 00:12:27.190
The first person in
the queue decides

00:12:27.190 --> 00:12:29.780
on product B of the five.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:31.970
The second person in the
queue isn't quite sure,

00:12:31.970 --> 00:12:35.120
kind of likes product C, but
is moved by the first person

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:37.530
to get product B, too.

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:40.470
Once the first two people
have gotten product B,

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:42.060
then the third person
is going to have

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:44.290
to have a lot of
information to choose

00:12:44.290 --> 00:12:47.550
one of the other products
because two people have ended

00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:52.860
up choosing product B. I think
with respect to a large number

00:12:52.860 --> 00:12:56.920
of social success stories,
including Rodriguez in South

00:12:56.920 --> 00:13:00.570
Africa and Rodriguez
in the United States,

00:13:00.570 --> 00:13:02.730
the deal maker or
the deal breaker

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:07.120
is whether you benefit from
an informational cascade.

00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:09.580
For many things,
including "Star Wars,"

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:12.550
there are reputational
cascades as well.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:16.910
If you didn't know, at certain
period in 1977, anything

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:20.250
about "Star Wars," and you
were, say, 17 years old,

00:13:20.250 --> 00:13:22.030
you are a loser.

00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:24.020
You had to know
about "Star Wars."

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:28.730
You would risk your reputation
among your peers if you didn't.

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:30.980
And if you had seen
it and didn't like it,

00:13:30.980 --> 00:13:33.060
you'd also risk your reputation.

00:13:33.060 --> 00:13:36.580
So you had to A, see
it, and B, like it.

00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:38.550
If you didn't like
it, you had to it

00:13:38.550 --> 00:13:40.800
in the sense of
saying you liked it.

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:42.950
And that put
reputational pressure

00:13:42.950 --> 00:13:45.500
on members of the population.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:48.690
Some things, and I hope
this is very familiar here,

00:13:48.690 --> 00:13:50.680
benefit from network effects.

00:13:50.680 --> 00:13:53.950
That people enjoy them because
other people enjoy them,

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:55.840
that's a kind of a
loose generalization

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:58.120
of the idea of network effects.

00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:00.310
And for "The Force
Awakens," a lot of people

00:14:00.310 --> 00:14:04.450
went because they thought
everyone was going.

00:14:04.450 --> 00:14:04.950
OK.

00:14:04.950 --> 00:14:07.550
Is that true for "Star Wars"?

00:14:07.550 --> 00:14:09.340
Is that the full account?

00:14:09.340 --> 00:14:10.130
Really?

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:11.510
Seriously?

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:13.550
Is "Star Wars" like
one of those kind

00:14:13.550 --> 00:14:15.900
of average songs
in the music lab

00:14:15.900 --> 00:14:20.920
experiment that exploded
because early people liked it?

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:25.260
I mean really and
seriously to be

00:14:25.260 --> 00:14:30.450
doubting the fullness of the
explanation I've just given.

00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:32.870
Think, if you would, about
the Arab Spring and the fall

00:14:32.870 --> 00:14:34.000
of communism.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.580
Surely the timing of
both of those events,

00:14:36.580 --> 00:14:39.030
highly unpredictable,
had a lot to do

00:14:39.030 --> 00:14:40.570
with what we're now discussing.

00:14:40.570 --> 00:14:42.300
And there's terrific
empirical work

00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:45.840
suggesting that informational
cascades and reputational

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:49.280
cascades were crucial
to when those happened.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:53.490
But the fall of
authoritarian governance

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:56.530
isn't just a product
of cascade effects.

00:14:56.530 --> 00:14:59.930
They're also
authoritarian governments,

00:14:59.930 --> 00:15:05.020
and what is sought to
replace them by the rebels

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:09.790
is something that has higher
intrinsic quality, which

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:13.520
is to suggest that to attribute
the success of "Star Wars"

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:18.671
solely to the explanation just
given is probably a mistake.

00:15:18.671 --> 00:15:19.170
OK.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:20.810
Second idea.

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:24.820
What "Star Wars" benefited from
is the appeal of the monomyth.

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:27.070
So there's a guy named
Joseph Campbell, discovered,

00:15:27.070 --> 00:15:31.800
by the way, by Jacqueline
Kennedy, President Kennedy's

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:34.200
wife, as an editor.

00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:38.670
Joseph Campbell said that there
is a monomyth in cultures where

00:15:38.670 --> 00:15:42.030
there's a hero's
journey-- Jesus, Buddha,

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:45.110
Mohammad, and many
others show all

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:47.600
or many features
of the monomyth--

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:51.420
where people receive at
a young age a challenge.

00:15:51.420 --> 00:15:52.950
They decline it.

00:15:52.950 --> 00:15:54.520
They find a mentor.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:55.810
They leave home.

00:15:55.810 --> 00:15:57.140
They're tested.

00:15:57.140 --> 00:15:58.670
They face dangers.

00:15:58.670 --> 00:16:00.010
They get help.

00:16:00.010 --> 00:16:05.790
They reunite in some sense
with home, and they celebrate.

00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:08.160
Now, that has universal appeal.

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:10.140
It's all of us.

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:13.660
Every human being's
journey is, in a way,

00:16:13.660 --> 00:16:16.360
the hero's journey,
which helps account

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:21.920
for its spectacular
appeal in any country,

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:24.240
basically, that you can name.

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:25.100
Spiderman.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:27.400
Hero's journey.

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:31.140
Jessica Jones, the
best heroic journey

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:33.570
in the last decade in my view.

00:16:33.570 --> 00:16:36.820
If you haven't seen it,
watch "Jessica Jones."

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:42.830
She is replicating the
monomyth in a distinctive way.

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:46.000
And Luke Skywalker,
no doubt about it.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.840
But there are a lot of monomyths
out there, and most of them

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:49.590
tanked.

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:51.350
You haven't even heard of them.

00:16:51.350 --> 00:16:54.250
So it can't be sufficient
for "Star Wars"

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:58.650
success, though it's true
that it tracked the monomyth.

00:16:58.650 --> 00:16:59.150
OK.

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:01.200
Third explanation.

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:03.990
"Star Wars" has many
possible meanings.

00:17:03.990 --> 00:17:07.109
You can easily see it as an
essentially Christian tale

00:17:07.109 --> 00:17:10.569
in which Anakin Skywalker
is a Christ-like figure who

00:17:10.569 --> 00:17:15.480
dies, in a way, for our sins,
finds salvation, and guarantees

00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:21.619
something like that to us
in a tale that in many ways

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:23.060
mimics the New Testament.

00:17:23.060 --> 00:17:25.690
You can see Luke's
journey in the same way.

00:17:25.690 --> 00:17:28.040
So the Christian
resonance in the tale

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:32.150
helps give it a kind
of cultural appeal.

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:33.890
You can see it as Freudian.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:35.340
No question about that.

00:17:35.340 --> 00:17:38.730
Anakin is in love with
his mother, who dies.

00:17:38.730 --> 00:17:42.180
He falls for, in a
literal way, a woman who's

00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:45.420
much older who
says Anakin, you'll

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:48.830
always be a little boy to me.

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:51.090
Kind of Freudian.

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:57.630
Both Luke and Anakin have
big-time father issues, and OK.

00:17:57.630 --> 00:18:00.650
You can see it as a
Jeffersonian tale that

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:04.420
would resonate in the United
States about rebellion

00:18:04.420 --> 00:18:08.300
and the need for a kind of
monitoring of potentially

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:10.500
authoritarian governance.

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:16.440
There are crazy theories about
Jar Jar Binks being a Sith Lord

00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:20.770
or about Han Solo having
the force or about

00:18:20.770 --> 00:18:23.220
the wonderfulness of the Empire.

00:18:23.220 --> 00:18:26.580
These are crazy theories,
but they're ingenious,

00:18:26.580 --> 00:18:29.360
and they can fit the tale.

00:18:29.360 --> 00:18:32.160
Does that have
explanatory power?

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:33.120
Some.

00:18:33.120 --> 00:18:36.790
But here's a pedantic word
on necessary and sufficient

00:18:36.790 --> 00:18:37.710
conditions.

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:39.770
If you want to explain
"Star Wars" success,

00:18:39.770 --> 00:18:41.725
we have to distinguish
between two.

00:18:41.725 --> 00:18:46.140
It may be a necessary condition
that it have multiple meanings.

00:18:46.140 --> 00:18:48.360
Maybe that makes it intriguing.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:50.640
But it's not a
sufficient condition.

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:52.490
There are a lot of
terrible things out there

00:18:52.490 --> 00:18:57.950
that have many meanings
that don't make $30 billion

00:18:57.950 --> 00:19:04.010
and probably what's being done
by the people who are focusing

00:19:04.010 --> 00:19:06.740
on many meanings as
the source of success

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:09.740
is that they're committing
a statistical error called

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:12.060
sampling on the
dependent variable.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:14.010
That is, they take
a variable that

00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:17.740
is connected with a bunch of
successful things, of which

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:19.970
"Star Wars" is one,
and then claiming

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:23.490
that that's causally
responsible for its success.

00:19:23.490 --> 00:19:25.420
But it turned out--
if it turned out

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:28.180
that the five culturally
most resonant things, let's

00:19:28.180 --> 00:19:32.150
say, in the last 50 years
were all made by someone who

00:19:32.150 --> 00:19:35.760
was born in December
or who had the letter

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:40.350
L in their last name, that would
not be causally responsible.

00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:43.500
And I think this is
suffering from that blunder.

00:19:43.500 --> 00:19:44.000
OK.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.360
Explanation number four.

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:48.230
What a lot of people
all over the world,

00:19:48.230 --> 00:19:50.150
and certainly in the
United States, like

00:19:50.150 --> 00:19:52.860
is tales of republics
and empires.

00:19:52.860 --> 00:19:56.990
The theory in the
saga, and its presaged

00:19:56.990 --> 00:20:01.010
in the beloved original trilogy,
it's very clearly spelled out

00:20:01.010 --> 00:20:04.790
in the underrated
prequels, is that democracy

00:20:04.790 --> 00:20:07.260
falls to thunderous applause.

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:11.930
And the idea is that republics
are vulnerable and fragile

00:20:11.930 --> 00:20:15.610
and that they fall in a kind
of predictable, somewhat

00:20:15.610 --> 00:20:17.310
stylized way.

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:25.140
The fall of Rome, the fall of
Germany, Stalin's authority,

00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:28.010
all had something
to do with a theme

00:20:28.010 --> 00:20:30.890
that "Star Wars"
is very alert to.

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:33.120
This does resonate,
and I think it

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:37.470
is accounting for the beginnings
of what we're seeing now,

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:40.670
which is a rebirth of
interest in the prequels

00:20:40.670 --> 00:20:43.200
because they are saying
something that connects

00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:45.240
at least with
developments in Europe

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:48.570
and possibly the United States.

00:20:48.570 --> 00:20:50.730
What I'm going to say
about that explanation

00:20:50.730 --> 00:20:53.810
is it captures some of
the appeal of "Star Wars,"

00:20:53.810 --> 00:20:56.860
but again, it's neither--
it's certainly not

00:20:56.860 --> 00:20:59.750
sufficient for cultural success.

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:01.610
You can tell a lot
of boring tales

00:21:01.610 --> 00:21:03.990
about republics
falling to empires,

00:21:03.990 --> 00:21:06.870
and it's not necessary.

00:21:06.870 --> 00:21:07.370
OK.

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:10.250
Here's a more interesting
explanation, I think.

00:21:10.250 --> 00:21:11.120
The zeitgeist.

00:21:11.120 --> 00:21:12.090
The culture.

00:21:12.090 --> 00:21:14.830
And here the idea is that
after the assassination

00:21:14.830 --> 00:21:17.085
of the Kennedys, Martin
Luther King, and Malcolm

00:21:17.085 --> 00:21:20.900
X, and the tulmult
of the Vietnam era,

00:21:20.900 --> 00:21:23.860
and malaise, which was
Jimmy Carter's term for what

00:21:23.860 --> 00:21:31.560
the country was in, the time was
kind of perfect for a new hope.

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:33.080
That's what the country wanted.

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:34.190
A new hope.

00:21:34.190 --> 00:21:37.150
A lift was needed,
and George Lucas

00:21:37.150 --> 00:21:40.130
delivered in on a
silver spaceship.

00:21:40.130 --> 00:21:42.070
That's exactly what happened.

00:21:42.070 --> 00:21:49.380
And many of the sociologically
most attuned critics

00:21:49.380 --> 00:21:52.420
of the question
I'm exploring now

00:21:52.420 --> 00:21:56.440
put their finger on this one,
and they say this is the one.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:21:59.660
I'm going to be very hard on
this explanation in a way that

00:21:59.660 --> 00:22:03.820
bears on "Star Wars" but
also on political success

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:07.980
and cultural success, Taylor
Swift and "Harry Potter."

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:11.460
I'm going to suggest that all
of these things that succeed,

00:22:11.460 --> 00:22:15.380
this is a tempting but very
problematic explanation.

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:20.040
The reason is it's always
possible to generate an ex post

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:22.320
zeitgeit explanation.

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:27.240
It's child's play to say the
most popular thing X succeeded

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:31.090
because of cultural
factors A, B, and C. You

00:22:31.090 --> 00:22:34.930
can say "Harry Potter"
after 9/11, of course.

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:38.840
Taylor Swift after the
recession, of course.

00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:41.840
But is that true?

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:44.230
Here's a way to think about it.

00:22:44.230 --> 00:22:47.030
Imagine that "Star
Wars" did great

00:22:47.030 --> 00:22:56.700
in the 1990s, the early
aughts, tomorrow, or the 1930s.

00:22:56.700 --> 00:22:59.780
We could easily generate
a cultural account

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:01.780
of why that happened,
and it would

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:06.440
be as plausible as the
ones that are out there.

00:23:06.440 --> 00:23:08.220
1930s, depression.

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:10.000
They needed a new hope.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.160
1990s, Clinton.

00:23:12.160 --> 00:23:15.110
They needed a new hope.

00:23:15.110 --> 00:23:18.920
1980s, conventionality.

00:23:18.920 --> 00:23:24.720
Luke Skywalker, perfect for
the earnestness of the times.

00:23:24.720 --> 00:23:25.710
Plausible?

00:23:25.710 --> 00:23:26.590
Yes.

00:23:26.590 --> 00:23:27.730
True?

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:28.800
No.

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:29.970
A fairy tale?

00:23:29.970 --> 00:23:31.710
Yes.

00:23:31.710 --> 00:23:32.620
OK.

00:23:32.620 --> 00:23:36.280
Here's explanation six.

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:40.150
"Star Wars" engages
intriguingly with the light side

00:23:40.150 --> 00:23:41.540
and the dark side.

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:43.840
William Blake, the
great English poet,

00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:47.840
wrote of the greatest religious
text in the English language.

00:23:47.840 --> 00:23:51.000
The reason John Milton,
who wrote "Paradise Lost,"

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:54.430
wrote in fetters when he
wrote of angels and God

00:23:54.430 --> 00:23:56.940
and at liberty when
of devils and hell

00:23:56.940 --> 00:24:00.130
is because he was a true
poet and of the devil's party

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:02.200
without knowing it.

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:04.880
That's a mouthful, and
it does account for some

00:24:04.880 --> 00:24:06.770
of the appeal of "Star Wars."

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:08.690
Notice, if you
would, Blake, it's

00:24:08.690 --> 00:24:10.520
not clear if he
actually believed this,

00:24:10.520 --> 00:24:14.990
but he's venturing the idea that
a true poet is of the devil's

00:24:14.990 --> 00:24:17.040
party without knowing it.

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:21.870
Blake also wrote in
one of his proverbs

00:24:21.870 --> 00:24:25.170
those who restrain their
desires do so because theirs is

00:24:25.170 --> 00:24:27.940
weak enough to be restrained.

00:24:27.940 --> 00:24:31.000
A brilliant essay on "Star
Wars" by Lydia Millet

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:34.175
says that Vader is the most
erotic figure in the "Star

00:24:34.175 --> 00:24:36.590
Wars" family, and
the only tragic one,

00:24:36.590 --> 00:24:39.510
and because of this, he
had a terrible beauty.

00:24:39.510 --> 00:24:43.760
He had an erotic charge
because he gets what he wants.

00:24:43.760 --> 00:24:46.790
He makes the dark
side seem sexy.

00:24:46.790 --> 00:24:48.880
That's her explanation.

00:24:48.880 --> 00:24:50.520
Is that relevant?

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:51.800
Oh, yeah.

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:53.690
No question that's relevant.

00:24:53.690 --> 00:24:57.200
But remember the pedantic words
about necessary and sufficient

00:24:57.200 --> 00:24:58.440
conditions.

00:24:58.440 --> 00:25:00.180
That's a caution.

00:25:00.180 --> 00:25:00.680
OK.

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:04.370
Now we're going to get to
my preferred explanations.

00:25:04.370 --> 00:25:08.640
There's a son, Luke.

00:25:08.640 --> 00:25:11.790
Anakin saves his son.

00:25:11.790 --> 00:25:14.750
Told repeatedly
by Yoda that fear

00:25:14.750 --> 00:25:17.890
is the path to the dark side
and you must be detached

00:25:17.890 --> 00:25:23.260
and not fear loss,
Anakin is attached.

00:25:23.260 --> 00:25:28.250
Luke saves his father
because of attachment.

00:25:28.250 --> 00:25:30.630
Anakin, in the most
moving scene to date

00:25:30.630 --> 00:25:32.935
of "Star Wars," and
he's called Anakin

00:25:32.935 --> 00:25:37.040
in the script for the first
time, says to Luke's plea,

00:25:37.040 --> 00:25:42.900
I must save you, father, Anakin
responds, you already have.

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:45.550
"Star Wars" is all
about fathers and sons.

00:25:45.550 --> 00:25:48.690
It can be generalized to
mothers and daughters.

00:25:48.690 --> 00:25:52.530
But the original six, they're
all about fathers and sons.

00:25:52.530 --> 00:25:57.460
And that appeal accounts for the
kind of depth of the attachment

00:25:57.460 --> 00:26:01.740
that "Star Wars" itself
produces in many of its viewers.

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:04.130
Since my book came
out, I can't tell you

00:26:04.130 --> 00:26:07.800
how often children--
mostly boys,

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:10.440
but some girls--
who are grown now

00:26:10.440 --> 00:26:13.220
have come up to me
misty-eyed and talked

00:26:13.220 --> 00:26:15.700
about what "Star
Wars" meant to them.

00:26:15.700 --> 00:26:21.730
And even more, I can't tell you
how often dads, often 60s, 70s,

00:26:21.730 --> 00:26:24.490
and 80s, have come
up to me and said,

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:28.820
I saw this with
my boy when young.

00:26:28.820 --> 00:26:33.830
And that is a big part of
the power of the movies.

00:26:33.830 --> 00:26:38.220
But it would be possible to
say that the father-son thing

00:26:38.220 --> 00:26:43.590
wouldn't work unless there
was a kind of dark mirror

00:26:43.590 --> 00:26:50.320
in the saga which tells us a
lot about agency and freedom.

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:54.100
George Lucas, mirroring
the tale of Luke

00:26:54.100 --> 00:26:58.320
in "Return of the
Jedi," with Anakin

00:26:58.320 --> 00:27:02.540
in "Revenge of the Sith,"
said-- this is Lucas-- Anakin

00:27:02.540 --> 00:27:04.680
says yes to the dark side.

00:27:04.680 --> 00:27:06.320
Luke says no.

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:11.230
And it's under very precisely
identical situations.

00:27:11.230 --> 00:27:14.040
There's a pervasive
disagreement in the saga.

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:16.150
It has everything
to do with freedom.

00:27:16.150 --> 00:27:19.860
It makes these all-American
movies, I think.

00:27:19.860 --> 00:27:23.700
The emperor thinks that life's
trajectory is foreordained.

00:27:23.700 --> 00:27:26.800
