00:42:59.070 --> 00:43:02.480
Let's make a few distinctions
that might be useful.

00:43:02.480 --> 00:43:04.870
So behavioral
economics, I think,

00:43:04.870 --> 00:43:08.650
is most usefully
understood as focusing

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:12.980
on how human beings depart
from economic understanding

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:14.770
as a rationality.

00:43:14.770 --> 00:43:19.580
So the fact that in New York
relatively recently, people

00:43:19.580 --> 00:43:22.940
were really scared of getting
Ebola, even though at that time

00:43:22.940 --> 00:43:25.340
more Americans had
married Kardashians

00:43:25.340 --> 00:43:28.550
than had died of
Ebola, and people

00:43:28.550 --> 00:43:31.590
weren't going around saying,
I might marry a Kardashian,

00:43:31.590 --> 00:43:34.280
either with terror or hope.

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:39.410
But the event of getting Ebola
was so available in the head

00:43:39.410 --> 00:43:41.810
that probability
judgements went awry,

00:43:41.810 --> 00:43:43.780
so people assess
probabilities often

00:43:43.780 --> 00:43:46.350
by thinking of what recently
comes to mind-- what

00:43:46.350 --> 00:43:48.040
most immediately comes to mind.

00:43:48.040 --> 00:43:50.580
That's a behavioral
economics finding.

00:43:50.580 --> 00:43:54.880
So departures from rationality
are people hate losses.

00:43:54.880 --> 00:43:58.880
They dislike losses more than
they like corresponding gains.

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:00.420
We can do that in this room.

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:04.300
Half of you, it's just
courtesy of the organizers,

00:44:04.300 --> 00:44:05.840
half of you at the
end of this talk

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:09.940
are going to have to put
$10-- sorry, sorry people--

00:44:09.940 --> 00:44:11.940
$10 on this podium.

